04617nam a22006855i 9780292748378DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927483787 a10.7560/7483612doi  a(DE-B1597)587172  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHT167.5.T4bF47 2014eb 7aARC0100002bisacsh04a307.1/216097642231 aFerguson, Cheryl Caldwell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHighland Park and River Oaks :bThe Origins of Garden Suburban Community Planning in Texas /cCheryl Caldwell Ferguson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter one . City Planning in Dallas and Houston: The Genesis of Large-Scale Suburban Community Planning and Architecture in Dallas and Houston -- tChapter two . The Planning and Development of Residential Communities in Dallas and Houston, 1850s–1920s -- tChapter three . Highland Park: “Just Beyond the City’s Dust and Smoke” -- tChapter four . Highland Park West: “The Crowning Achievement of Highland Park” and the Highland Park Shopping Village -- tChapter five . The Hogg Brothers, Hugh Potter, and the Development of River Oaks: “Homes to Last for All Time” -- tChapter six . Highland Park and River Oaks: Their Texas Influence and Permanence -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early twentieth century, developers from Baltimore to Beverly Hills built garden suburbs, a new kind of residential community that incorporated curvilinear roads and landscape design as picturesque elements in a neighborhood. Intended as models for how American cities should be rationally, responsibly, and beautifully modernized, garden suburban communities were fragments of a larger (if largely imagined) garden city—the mythical “good” city of U.S. city-planning practices of the 1920s. This extensively illustrated book chronicles the development of the two most fully realized garden suburbs in Texas, Dallas’s Highland Park and Houston’s River Oaks. Cheryl Caldwell Ferguson draws on a wealth of primary sources to trace the planning, design, financing, implementation, and long-term management of these suburbs. She analyzes homes built by such architects as H. B. Thomson, C. D. Hill, Fooshee & Cheek, John F. Staub, Birdsall P. Briscoe, and Charles W. Oliver. She also addresses the evolution of the shopping center by looking at Highland Park’s Shopping Village, which was one of the first in the nation. Ferguson sets the story of Highland Park and River Oaks within the larger story of the development of garden suburban communities in Texas and across America to explain why these two communities achieved such prestige, maintained their property values, became the most successful in their cities in the twentieth century, and still serve as ideal models for suburban communities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecture and societyzTexasxHistory. 0aCity planningzTexasxHistory. 0aGarden suburbszTexasxHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74836140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292748378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292748378/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK